| Rank | Dataset               | Key Reasons for Difficulty Level                                                                          |
| ---- | --------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1    | MNIST                 | Low resolution (28×28), grayscale, 10 classes, centered digits, clean background, low variability         |
| 2    | Dogs vs Cats (Kaggle) | Binary classification, but real-world variation in pose, lighting, and background                         |
| 3    | Flowers-17            | 17 classes, limited images per class, inter-class similarity, natural background variation                |
| 4    | CIFAR-10              | 10 object classes, low resolution (32×32), high intra-class variation, cluttered backgrounds              |
| 5    | ImageNet              | 1000 classes, massive scale, fine-grained distinctions, high intra-class variation, real-world complexity |


Explanation of Ranking

MNIST (Easiest)
MNIST is relatively simple due to its low-resolution grayscale images and clean backgrounds. The digits are centered and normalized, and the number of classes is limited to 10. Variation exists in handwriting styles, but the task lacks background noise and real-world complexity.

Dogs vs Cats
Although it involves real-world images with varied lighting and poses, it is still a binary classification task. The small number of classes reduces decision boundary complexity, making it easier than multi-class natural image datasets.

Flowers-17
With 17 categories and fewer images per class, Flowers-17 increases difficulty. Many flower species look visually similar, increasing inter-class ambiguity. Limited data also raises overfitting risk.

CIFAR-10
Despite having only 10 classes, CIFAR-10 is more difficult because of low image resolution and complex natural scenes. Objects appear at different scales and angles, and backgrounds are cluttered. Distinguishing object structure at 32×32 resolution is challenging.

ImageNet (Hardest)
ImageNet includes over one million images across 1000 classes. It contains fine-grained categories (e.g., similar dog breeds), extreme intra-class variation, and real-world backgrounds. The scale and diversity significantly increase classification complexity.


The Illusion of Accuracy:
Accuracy alone does not fully reflect model quality.
A model achieving 99% accuracy on MNIST is not necessarily superior to a model achieving 72% on Flowers-17.
MNIST is simpler, with clean images and low complexity. Flowers-17 contains more visual similarity between 
classes and fewer samples per category, making high accuracy harder to achieve.

Similarly, 95% accuracy on CIFAR-10 may still hide problems:
Dataset leakage between training and testing data
Overfitting to background patterns instead of object structure
Limited generalization to new distributions
Therefore, evaluation must consider dataset complexity, class variation, robustness, and real-world applicability—not just a single accuracy number.

Dataset Size and Modeling Strategy:

Small Dataset Scenario (≈80 images per class):
Training from scratch is risky due to overfitting.
The preferred strategy is transfer learning:

Use a pretrained model (e.g., trained on ImageNet):
Freeze early layers to preserve general features like edges and textures.
Fine-tune later layers to adapt to the new task.
This approach reuses learned representations and reduces overfitting risk.


Large-Scale Scenario (ImageNet-scale):
With millions of labeled images:
Training from scratch becomes feasible.
High-capacity deep networks can be used.
Computational demands increase (GPUs, distributed training).
Regularization (data augmentation, dropout, weight decay) remains important.
Large datasets reduce variance-related overfitting but introduce engineering and computational challenges.